How Relic compares to Shelf, when to use each, and where it fits alongside Serverpod.
The Shelf Problem
Shelf has been Dart’s go-to HTTP framework for years. It is stable, well-documented, and used in production.
It is also frustrating to work with if you care about type safety.
Headers are Map<String, String>. Route parameters are Map<String, String>. Middleware receives and returns Handler, a function type, not a typed pipeline. You spend a lot of time extracting and casting things that should be typed by default.
Relic, built by the Serverpod team, takes Shelf’s composable middleware idea and rebuilds it with proper type safety throughout.

Type-Safe Headers
In Shelf, you read a header like this:
final contentType = request.headers['content-type'];
// String?, hope you spelled it rightIn Relic:
final contentType = request.headers.contentType;
// MediaType?, has .mimeType, .charset, .parametersEvery standard header has a typed accessor. The compiler catches typos. You don’t need to remember the exact casing of Content-Type vs content-type.
Writing response headers is the same story:
return Response.ok(
body: Body.fromString(jsonEncode(data)),
headers: Headers.response(
contentType: MediaType.applicationJson,
cacheControl: CacheControl.noStore,
),
);
Trie Routing
Relic uses a trie data structure for route matching, the same approach used by most production HTTP routers in Go and Rust.
final router = Router()
..get('/api/v1/users', listUsers)
..get('/api/v1/users/<id>', getUser)
..post('/api/v1/users/<id>/trips', createTrip)
..delete('/api/v1/users/<id>', deleteUser);Path parameters are automatically extracted and passed as typed arguments:
Future<Response> getUser(Request request, String id) async {
final user = await db.findUser(id);
// id is String, no casting, no null check on params map
...
}Route matching is O(log n), irrelevant for most projects, but a useful property if you’re building a public API with hundreds of routes.

Composable Middleware
Relic inherits Shelf’s pipeline pattern, which is one of the cleaner middleware composition APIs in the Dart ecosystem:
final handler = const Pipeline()
.addMiddleware(logRequests())
.addMiddleware(corsHeaders())
.addMiddleware(authenticate(secret: Env.jwtSecret))
.addMiddleware(rateLimit(maxPerMinute: 60))
.addHandler(router.call);Each middleware is a function that wraps the next handler. The pipeline is explicit and readable. Order matters, authentication before rate limiting, etc., and the order is obvious from reading the code.

WebSocket Support
Relic 1.1.0 added built-in WebSocket support:
router.get('/ws', (Request request) {
if (request.isUpgradeRequest) {
return request.upgradeToWebSocket(
onMessage: (message) => handleMessage(message),
onDone: () => cleanupConnection(),
);
}
return Response.badRequest();
});Clean integration with the rest of the routing, no separate WebSocket server to manage.

Relic vs Shelf vs Serverpod
Shelf, when you need maximum ecosystem compatibility. More packages are built for Shelf than for Relic. If you need a specific middleware that only exists for Shelf, use Shelf.
Relic, when you want better type safety than Shelf provides, and you don’t need the full Serverpod infrastructure. Webhook handlers, lightweight API gateways, serverless functions.
Serverpod, when you want code generation, typed client-server communication, ORM, caching, and the full framework. For a Flutter app that needs a real backend, Serverpod is the better starting point.
I use all three. Serverpod for my main backends (Arriva, Chapr, Asami, DegenBot). Relic for lightweight HTTP services and webhook endpoints. Shelf when a dependency forces it.

What I Actually Use It For
The most practical use case I have found for Relic: webhook receivers.
A Payment webhook arrives at a URL. You validate the HMAC signature, parse the event, and update your database. This doesn’t need Serverpod’s full infrastructure, it’s a single POST endpoint with some business logic.
final handler = const Pipeline()
.addMiddleware(validateHmac(secret: Env.paystackSecret))
.addHandler((Request request) async {
final body = await request.readAsString();
final event = PaystackEvent.fromJson(jsonDecode(body));
await processWebhookEvent(event);
return Response.ok('');
});await serve(handler, InternetAddress.anyIPv4, 8080);Relic handles the HTTP layer cleanly. My business logic handles the rest.

